b"[![](../../cdshop/cdinfo.jpg)](../../cdshop/index.htm)  \n[Sacred Texts](../../index.htm)  [Hinduism](../index.htm)  [Index](index.htm)\n[Previous](sbe48513.htm)  [Next](sbe48515.htm)\n\n* * *\n\n17\\. According to some (a class of good works) other than these, of both\nkinds.\n\nThe text quoted above from one _s_ akha ('His friends enter upon his good\ndeeds') refers to good works other than the Agnihotra and the rest, the only\nobject of which is to give rise to knowledge, viz. to all those manifold good\nworks, previous or subsequent to the attaining to knowledge, the results of\nwhich are obstructed by other works of greater strength. Those texts also\nwhich declare works not to cling or to be destroyed through knowledge refer to\nthis same class of works.--The next Sutra recalls the fact, already previously\nestablished, that the results of works actually performed may somehow be\nobstructed.\n\n* * *\n\n[Next: 18. ... 'whatever he does with knowledge.'](sbe48515.htm)\n\n"